\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Amanita muscaria
\f1\i0 , commonly known as the 
\f2\b fly agaric
\f1\b0  or 
\f2\b fly amanita
\f1\b0 , is a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basidiomycete"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 basidiomycete}} of the genus {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanita}}. It is also a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscimol_mushroom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 muscimol mushroom}}. Native throughout the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperate"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 temperate}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boreal_ecosystem"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 boreal}} regions of the Northern Hemisphere, 
\f0\i Amanita muscaria
\f1\i0  has been unintentionally {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introduced_species"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 introduced}} to many countries in the Southern Hemisphere, generally as a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbiont"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 symbiont}} with pine and birch plantations, and is now a true {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmopolitan_distribution"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 cosmopolitan}} species. It {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mycorrhiza"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 associates}} with various {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deciduous"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 deciduous}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coniferous"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 coniferous}} trees. \
Arguably the most iconic {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toadstool"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 toadstool}} species, the fly agaric is a large white-{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamella_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 gilled}}, white-spotted, usually red mushroom, and is one of the most recognizable and widely encountered in popular culture. \
Although classified as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisonous_mushroom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 poisonous}}, reports of human deaths resulting from its ingestion are extremely rare. After {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parboiling"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 parboiling}} twice with water draining\'97which weakens its toxicity and breaks down the mushroom's psychoactive substances\'97it is eaten in parts of Europe, Asia, and North America. 
\f0\i Amanita muscaria
\f1\i0  is noted for its {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hallucinogenic"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 hallucinogenic}} properties, with its main psychoactive constituents being the compounds {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibotenic_acid"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 ibotenic acid}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscimol"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 muscimol}}. The mushroom was used as an intoxicant and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entheogen"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 entheogen}} by the indigenous {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peoples_of_Siberia"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 peoples of Siberia}} and by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A1mi"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 S\'e1mi}}, and has a religious significance in these cultures. There has been much speculation on possible traditional use of this mushroom as an intoxicant in other places such as the Middle East, Eurasia, North America, and Scandinavia. \
